        "content": "<p> <strong>Banū Aws </strong>are also known simply as Aws. They constituted one of the principal Arabian tribes of Yathrib, the other being Banū Khazraj, who were more numerous and powerful. Both Aws and Khazraj shared the common title and honor of being Helpers (<em>al-Anṣār</em>) after the Migration (<em>al-Hijra</em>). Both were pure Arabs (<em>al-‘Arab al-‘Āriba</em>), descending from Qaḥṭān and not from Abraham and the Arabized Arabs (<em>al-‘Arab al-Musta‘riba</em>) through his descendent ‘Adnān. During the pre-Islamic era Banū Aws and Banū Khazraj had also been linked by the joint name of Banū Qayla (the Children of Qayla). In Arabic, “<em>aws</em>” is a word for “gift,” and Banū Aws had taken their name from <em>Aws Manāt</em>, meaning “gift of [the goddess] Manāt.” Consequently, the Prophet Muḥammad renamed them “<em>Aws-Allāh</em>” (the Gift of God). Both Banū Aws and Banū Khazraj had migrated to Yathrib in pre-Islamic times around the year 300 CE after the rupture of the Great Dam of Mar’ib. At that time, Yathrib was dominated by its Jewish tribes, and Banū Qayla became subordinate to them for a time. During the fifth century CE, however, Banū Qayla became the dominant grouping within Yathrib, and the Jews became subordinate to them. At the time of the <em>Hijra</em>, the chieftain of Banū Aws was Sa‘d ibn Mu‘ādh. </p>",
        "sectionId": "web-extension-book-five-god-s-last-messenger-muhammad-best-known-most-closely-observed-most-successful-of-all-god-s-prophets"
